title: For Sale:  AR accessories.
postcontent:
Replace your bland old parts with some fancy new (and functional) equipment:
 
1/2 x 28 fishbone muzzle brake (Crush washer & sizing nut included.) $15
 
Butterfly charging handle. Enhance your grip and add ambidextrous pull. You can use these to pull either left or right and charge under scopes. Very fond of mine. $20
 
Magpul rail attachment flip sights, fully adjustable. Great for main or backup use. Pair for $15
 
Do it yourselfer no walk/anti rotation pins. Good for 80% receiver builds. I'll sell these as a 3-pin set (Includes 3 pins and 3 screws) for only $2
Important note on the pins: I'm selling them cheap and as a DIY project. These pins are 25mm long (I believe AR receivers are 23mm?) I bought these in bulk when I didn't want to spend $6 a pair for my 80% receiver and knew these should only be a $1 a pin import. At any rate, the connection screw and insert are long and there is plenty of room to work with to grind/cut. Anyone that can complete an 80% shouldn't have a problem resizing these screws a few mm. These will do the job and lock up tight, as they did on mine.
No one is perfect and no one gets every cut right every time. :) Therefore I'm including the extra pin and screw for DIY mistake wiggle room.
I can also supply washers and 2 pins to lock them up without grinding/cutting.
The biggest issues I've seen with 80% builds (And experienced) are improperly sized holes or misaligned holes. Both will cause the pins to migrate and fall out. Especially when fast firing. Other people like these pins because they say the friction and grind from movement and heat from a lot of fire can bore out and warp the receivers. I haven't experienced that personally but I do feel it might be an issue with the polymer lowers after quite a bit of use. Either way these screws will lock into place and not alow the pins to migrate or roll at a great price.

title: For Sale:  Custom F Class/Benchrest  Competition Rifle
postcontent:
Leaving the hobby and am ready to let this amazing rifle go. This is a <0.25 moa rifle set up for 1,000-yard competitions.

This custom built rifle was built by one of the sports most decorated champions and has his signature chambering in 6mm BR. At the core of the rifle is a Savage dual port stainless steel action with a 30” Krieger barrel with a straight taper 1.25” diameter barrel at a 1-8 twist. A 20 moa rail sits on top to allow for long-range optics. An adjustable Rifle Basix trigger (4-ounce to 3-pound) set for an 8-ounce release with zero creep has been installed. The masters at Gre-Tan Rifles worked the bolt to insure the absolute most consistent primer strike. The entire package sits in an incredibly beautiful laminate real wood stock. I attached a cheek weld on the butt stock that insures consistent eye relief and height for the scope. The rifle will come with a hardshell rolling case and the custom Redding reloading dies.

I selected the Sightron SIII SS 10-50x60 Side Focus Long Range Riflescope with fine crosshairs and extended sunshade for the task of reaching out and touching that target for its quality and value.

As I stated, I am leaving the hobby so I will be grouping everything to be sold individually or as a group, or as a 100% turnkey ready to compete setup.

I am one of those people who never scrimps when it comes to anything I do. F Class competition shooting was no exception. In the Competition Group, I am including everything you need to be competitive on the firing line. The flagship of this setup is the custom built front rest from Targetshooting. This is a 25-pound rest and is capable of micro-adjustments and is incredibly solid, matched with one of Bruno’s Shooting Supply/Edgewood leather rear bag that weighs in at about 10-pounds. This combination makes for an incredibly stable and repeatable shooting platform. Laying in the dirt or on a cement firing line is made much more comfortable with a padded trifold shooting mat. The one skill that separates good shooters from great shooters is their ability to read the wind. One of the most important methods of reading the winds is the ability to read the heat waves at intermediate ranges. To do this, most competitive shooters use a spotting scope on a tripod focused to these intermediate ranges.
